{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01VbPnH6oPjnPKtUquGA4KbZ","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Repository Layout\n     2→\n     3→```\n     4→new-ralph-burning/\n     5→├── multibackend-orchestration/   # legacy codebase (read-only reference)\n     6→├── ralph-burning-rewrite/        # new code we are creating\n     7→└── rb.md                         # this spec\n     8→```\n     9→\n    10→* **`multibackend-orchestration/`** — the original codebase. Treat as **read-only**. All `src/` paths referenced in this document (e.g. `src/workflow/orchestrator.rs`) live under this directory.\n    11→* **`ralph-burning-rewrite/`** — the greenfield rewrite target. All new code goes here.\n    12→\n    13→# Executive Summary\n    14→\n    15→The legacy codebase (`multibackend-orchestration/`) is a local AI engineering orchestrator with a much broader scope than “a Rust CLI that runs planner / implementer / reviewer loops.” It currently contains at least these real capabilities:\n    16→\n    17→* structured delivery orchestration with planning, implementation, QA, review, completion, and final review\n    18→* a separate quick-dev workflow\n    19→* workspace and project state management under `.ralph/`\n    20→* PRD generation pipelines\n    21→* daemon / GitHub issue and PR automation\n    22→* a large binary-level conformance suite\n    23→\n    24→That picture is visible in `src/workflow/{orchestrator,quick_dev_orchestrator}.rs`, `src/project/*`, `src/backend/*`, `src/prd/*`, `src/daemon/*`, and `src/validate/*` (all under `multibackend-orchestration/`).\n    25→\n    26→The rewrite lives in **`ralph-burning-rewrite/`**, with a new workspace root **`.ralph-burning/`** and a fully new storage model. The legacy codebase should be used as a **behavior and domain reference only**. The rewrite should not preserve or read/write legacy `.ralph` state, legacy markdown artifact formats, legacy loop directories, or legacy git checkpoint encodings.\n    27→\n    28→The recommended target is a **Rust modular monolith** with explicit bounded contexts and selective hexagonal architecture around real side-effect boundaries. The most important design changes are:\n    29→\n    30→* replace “standard orchestrator vs quick-dev orchestrator” with a **shared workflow engine**\n    31→* make **flow presets** first-class and fixed per project\n    32→* support exactly these built-in flow presets in v1:\n    33→\n    34→  * `standard`\n    35→  * `quick_dev`\n    36→  * `docs_change`\n    37→  * `ci_improvement`\n    38→* replace markdown-as-machine-protocol with **structured stage contracts** using validated JSON payloads\n    39→* keep markdown as a **rendered human artifact**, not as the workflow protocol\n    40→* separate **durable project history** from **ephemeral runtime/debug logs**\n    41→* modernize the CLI around coherent nouns and verbs\n    42→\n    43→Recommended bounded contexts:\n    44→\n    45→* **Workspace Governance**\n    46→* **Project & Run Record**\n    47→* **Workflow Composition**\n    48→* **Agent Execution**\n    49→* **Requirements Drafting**\n    50→* **Automation Runtime**\n    51→* **Conformance Specification**\n    52→\n    53→The biggest risks are architectural, not technical:\n    54→\n    55→* rebuilding giant orchestrators under new names\n    56→* over-generalizing into a workflow DSL too early\n    57→* letting stage markdown remain a protocol instead of rendered output\n    58→* allowing flow-specific state to leak back into the project model\n    59→* under-specifying operator-facing behavior like `history`, `tail`, `rollback`, `flow show`, and daemon routing\n    60→\n    61→The right rewrite is decisive: a greenfield modular monolith, typed workflow kernel, built-in flow presets, mandatory structured stage payloads across all supported backends, and a new conformance suite that captures desired behavior rather than legacy file formats.\n    62→\n    63→# Current System Summary\n    64→\n    65→## Core purpose\n    66→\n    67→Today the repo implements a local-first AI software-delivery orchestrator that coordinates multiple AI backends to perform engineering work inside a repository. It persists state locally, integrates with git, produces readable artifacts, and exposes operator controls for running, inspecting, resuming, validating, rolling back, generating PRDs, and automating GitHub-driven work.\n    68→\n    69→## Main user/operator workflows in the current system\n    70→\n    71→### Standard delivery flow\n    72→\n    73→The main workflow currently includes:\n    74→\n    75→* optional prompt review\n    76→* planning\n    77→* implementation\n    78→* QA\n    79→* review\n    80→* commit/checkpoint progression\n    81→* completion panel / acceptance QA\n    82→* final review and amendment restart logic\n    83→\n    84→This is concentrated in `src/workflow/orchestrator.rs`, with persistence and artifact support spread across `src/project/*`, `src/git/*`, `src/workspace/*`, and `src/config/*`.\n    85→\n    86→### Quick-dev flow\n    87→\n    88→The current repo has a separate flow with its own orchestration path:\n    89→\n    90→* PlanAndImplement\n    91→* CodexReview\n    92→* ApplyFixes\n    93→* FinalReview\n    94→\n    95→This is implemented in `src/workflow/quick_dev_orchestrator.rs` and surfaced through separate CLI commands in `src/cli/quick_dev_*`.\n    96→\n    97→### PRD workflows\n    98→\n    99→The repo contains at least three requirements-related paths:\n   100→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01X5aLsQAFgiJ96xUkfjGDzF","session_id":"4dd21658-c77f-461a-9d96-b900bdfee06f","uuid":"67252677-60f5-4893-99ff-dc786042327f"}
